  "color_desc": {
    "kicker": "The color · in plain words",
    "title_html": "What you're <em>looking</em> at.",
    "prose_paragraphs": [
      "Traditional architectural-shingle brown. Shenandoah is a workhorse color on craftsman, traditional, and Tudor-style homes where the roof is meant to grow out of the landscape rather than contrast against it. The granule blend uses warm tobacco and weathered-wood accents to keep the surface visually alive.",
      "Look closely and you can pick out three or four granule shades inside the blend. The eye stops registering them at conversational distance, but the layered texture is why warm-brown asphalt roofs photograph as 'rich' rather than 'flat'.",
      "Pairs cleanly with brick red, cream, warm white, sage, and natural-wood siding. Slightly less flexible than the gray family on cool or modern color palettes, but unbeatable on traditional elevations."
    ],
